  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Prior to the 20th century, there were few specific laws targeting money laundering\n- Some financial crimes existed, but comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks were not yet developed\n\n2. United States Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major U.S. legislation requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970) - Provided legal mechanisms to combat organized crime financial activities\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n\n3. International Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Established international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created recommendations for global financial institutions\n\n4. Post-9/11 Expansion\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) expanded AML regulations\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing\n- Enhanced reporting and compliance requirements\n\n5. Ongoing Global Cooperation\n- Continued refinement of international AML standards\n- Increasing technological approaches to detecting financial crimes\n\nThis overview represents a simplified progression of money laundering legal developments.",
